RABIES, CANINE - UZBEKISTAN (SURXONDARYO): HUMAN EXPOSURE
************************************************
A ProMED-mail post
<http://www.promedmail.org>
ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
<http://www.isid.org>

Date: Fri 21 Jul 2006
From: ProMED-mail Russian Correspondent Natalia Pshenichnaya
<crane@aaanet.ru>
Source: Pravda.ru, Mon 17 Jul 2006
[trans. from Russian Corresp. Arnak Stepanyan; edited]
<http://www.pravda.ru/news/health/17-07-2006/190894-sobaka-0>

A [rabid] stray dog has bitten 12 people in the Surxondaryo [province] of
Uzbekistan.

All of the victims have been admitted to the Altinsaysk Regional Hospital.
According to the Interfax News agency, the Hospital Director stated that
veterinarians had confirmed that the dog was rabid.

The hospital administration stated that the condition of all 12 patients
remains normal and that they are receiving appropriate medical care. The
local authorities are carrying out an urgent survey of the population to
identify any other cases of exposure to dog bite.

--
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>

[A map of Uzbekistan can be accessed via
<http://www.un.org/Depts/Cartographic/english/htmain.htm>. - Mod.CP]
[ProMED has never before carried a report specifically on rabies in
Uzbekistan. However, the country shares borders with the Osh region of
Kyrgyzstan, and with Kazakhstan, both of which have reported rabies before --
see refs. below -- and rabies is endemic across the whole region. - Mod.JW]
